    id: "p-rmc1-02",
    title: "Borrowed Voices: A Novelist on Being Translated",
    text: "The first time I read myself in French, I did not recognise the woman who had written the book. She was wittier than I am, for one thing, and more certain of her opinions; her sentences arrived at their destinations with a click, like well-made drawers, whereas mine — I had always privately felt — tend to shuffle in sideways, apologising. My translator, when I mentioned this over lunch, was unrepentant. 'French does not shuffle,' she said, and speared an olive with what I chose not to interpret as emphasis.\n\nAuthors are supposed to agonise about what is lost in translation, and interviewers ask me about it with a solicitous tilt of the head, as though enquiring after a chronic illness. I disappoint them. What preoccupies me is not what is lost but what is added, and by whom, and whether I am entitled to sign for it. Reviewers in Paris praised the 'dry precision' of my style. I do not have a dry precision. I have a damp approximation, which Claudine, sentence by sentence, wrung out and pressed. When the book won a small prize there, I accepted it with the uneasy graciousness of a woman being congratulated on a cake her neighbour baked.\n\nIt would be tidy to conclude that the French novel is simply Claudine's, and some translation theorists would encourage me to say so, with footnotes. But that will not do either, and not merely because my name is on the cover in larger type — an arrangement whose injustice I note annually and do nothing about. The book's evasions are mine; its architecture of withheld information, its habit of arriving at feeling through the back stairs of household detail — none of that is Claudine's invention. She built a new house, but to my plans, on my awkward plot of land. What unsettles me is subtler: her house is better lit. Readers see at once things I had half-hidden, sometimes deliberately, sometimes because I lacked the nerve to expose them. Translation, I have come to think, is less a window than an interrogation lamp.\n\nThe process runs the other way, too, which nobody warned me about. Since working with translators I have begun, insidiously, to pre-translate myself: to weed out the pun that will not travel, the schoolyard rhyme that will need a footnote in Seoul, the joke that depends on a brand of biscuit discontinued in 1987. Friends who read my recent drafts say the prose has become cleaner. They intend it as a compliment, and I bank it as one, but late at night I do the accounting differently and wonder whether 'cleaner' is what a voice sounds like when it has started checking its passport at every border. There is a kind of writer, increasingly rewarded, who composes in her own language as though already translated, every sentence pre-cleared through customs. I have caught myself becoming her, and the catching, so far, is the only resistance I can claim.\n\nAnd yet — the ledger has another column. My German translator sent me, with his queries, a list of what he called 'load-bearing ambiguities': eleven places where my English could mean two things at once and he must choose. I had been aware of perhaps four of them. The other seven had been operating in the dark, holding up floors I did not know I had built. No reader, no critic, certainly no interviewer had ever found them; it took a man paid by the word to rebuild my book in another language to discover what the book was made of. Translators are the only people who read the way writers fear and hope to be read — with total attention and no mercy.\n\nSo when I am asked, with the sympathetic tilt, what is lost, I have taken to answering: mostly illusions. The illusion that the voice on the page is bone rather than cartilage. The illusion that a book is finished when it is published, rather than each time someone rebuilds it. What survives translation, it turns out, is not the sentence at all but the thing the sentence was circling — and there is no flattery, and no exposure, quite like watching a stranger circle it more elegantly in a language you will never fully possess.",
