    title: "Between Tides: A Naturalist at the Estuary",
    text: "The guidebooks call the estuary a boundary, which tells you the guidebooks were written from dry land. Stand out on the flats at half-tide, ankle-deep in a substance that has not decided whether it is territory or weather, and the word dissolves. An estuary is not a line between river and sea but a negotiation between them, conducted twice daily, in public, with the moon presiding and no settlement ever reached. I have kept notes on this negotiation for eleven years now, and the chief thing I have learned is how much of my early notetaking was an attempt to make the place hold still.\n\nMud has an image problem, and the estuary suffers for it. Visitors gaze across a mile of gleaming ooze and see absence: no trees, no drama, nothing, they say, there. In fact they are looking at one of the most productive surfaces on the planet — richer, acre for acre, than the wheatfield they admired from the train — but its productivity is conducted in private, an inch below the shine. A single handful of this ooze holds more living things than the wood behind my house. The spectacle is all understatement; the estuary is a fortune that dresses badly. It took me years to stop apologising for it to visitors, and I note, without pride, that I stopped only when I noticed the visitors' disappointment no longer registered. The place had rearranged my sense of what counts as an event.\n\nWhat counts, out here, is mostly arithmetic. The bar-tailed godwits arriving each autumn have flown from Siberia; some, the trackers now tell us, without pausing. What looks from the sea wall like idle probing — that leisurely, needle-billed stitching of the mud — is a creature refilling, against a deadline, the fuel it burned crossing the roof of the world. A godwit misjudging the estuary's yield by a few per cent does not have a lean winter; it has no spring. I try to hold onto this when a dog, joyous and blameless, scatters five hundred birds into the November air and their owner, meeting my look, says they're only birds and they landed again, didn't they? They did. Each unplanned flight is a withdrawal from an account already overdrawn, and the ledger is settled in the Arctic, out of sight, where no one who loves dogs will ever have to audit it.\n\nI resist, these days, the language of tragedy, though the estuary offers material enough. Engineers walled off the upper marshes in my grandfather's time; the sea, patient beyond all human institutions, is now taking them back, and planners hold consultations about 'managed retreat' in village halls smelling of instant coffee and grief. I attend, and say my piece about salt marsh absorbing wave energy, carbon, nitrogen — the utilitarian catechism one recites because it is what committees can hear. What I do not say, because there is no agenda item for it, is that I have come to admire the sea's paperwork: its slow, unanswerable repossession, filed twice daily, of what was always mortgaged.\n\nPeople ask what the estuary has taught me, expecting, I think, serenity. The honest answer is punctuality. The tide is the last great enforcer of appointments; it does not reschedule, and its penalties for inattention run from wet boots to the coastguard helicopter. Living by the tide table restores a relation our species has mostly engineered away: an authority that cannot be lobbied. I find this restful in a way I struggle to justify to friends whose freedoms are all indoors. Twice a day, something vast declines to consult me. Twice a day, I am put, gently and absolutely, in my place — and my place, it turns out, is a specific patch of glistening mud, between a particular river and its particular sea, for as long as the negotiation lasts.\n\nOn the last spring tide, I watched the water come in over the flats faster than a person can comfortably walk, silvering the channels, lifting the moored boats from their sulk, erasing eleven years of my footprints in forty minutes. A younger self would have found the erasure melancholy and written it up as such. I have kept better notes since I stopped keeping score. The estuary is not a boundary and it is not a metaphor. It is a schedule, and I am on it, briefly, along with everything else.",
