    title: "The Fireground and the Chessboard: Expertise, Intuition and Their Impostors",
    text: "The fireground commander who ordered his crew out of a burning house seconds before the floor collapsed could not, when interviewed afterwards, say why he had done it. He spoke of a feeling, something wrong with the fire — too quiet, too hot for its size — and researchers who later reconstructed the incident found that his 'feeling' was a rapid, unconscious reading of cues he could not name: the blaze was beneath him, in the basement, and some sub-verbal accountant in his head had totted up the evidence and issued its verdict as dread. Stories like this have made intuition respectable again, after a century in which serious people were expected to apologise for it. They have also, less happily, made it fashionable, and fashion is where the trouble starts.\n\nFor the fireground commander's gift is real but conditional, and the conditions are strict. Decades of studies converge on an unglamorous formula: intuition is trustworthy exactly where the world is regular enough to have patterns, where the practitioner has had prolonged exposure to those patterns, and — the clause most often forgotten — where practice has been accompanied by feedback that is swift and unambiguous. The chess master glances at a position and the strong move suggests itself, because chess is a closed lawful world and every blunder of her apprenticeship was punished within moments. The nurse who senses an infant 'going off' hours before the monitors agree has spent years in a ward where such judgements meet their verdicts by morning. Remove any leg of the tripod and the same subjective glow of certainty persists — while its correlation with reality quietly falls away.\n\nThis is the finding with teeth, and it bites in high places. Study after study has ranked professional forecasters of political and market events at or near chance, their confidence untouched by their record; the interviewer who 'just knows' within ninety seconds which candidate will flourish is consulting a fluent, worthless oracle. Note what these domains share: irregular environments, feedback that arrives late, garbled, or never, and — crucially — no penalty for error that attaches to the intuition itself. The pundit whose prediction fails is rarely confronted with the failure; the interviewer never meets the candidates she rejected. Intuition in such settings is not compressed expertise. It is compressed autobiography — prejudice wearing experience's uniform, and drawing its salary.\n\nThe seductions run deeper than laziness. Intuitive judgement feels different from guessing — immediate, unbidden, carrying its own certificate of authenticity — and the feeling is identical whether the underlying pattern-library is the fireground commander's or the pundit's. Nature, having equipped us with a signal, neglected to equip us with a gauge for its reliability. Worse, the fluency that comes with mere familiarity mimics the fluency that comes from calibrated skill: after twenty years, the bad interviewer is not better, merely faster, her errors upholstered in confidence. Experience, we should say more often, is not a synonym for expertise. One can have twenty years of experience or the same year twenty times, and from the inside the two are indistinguishable.\n\nIt does not follow that we should hand everything to the algorithms and the checklists, though in the irregular domains the humble linear model does, embarrassingly often, outperform the star. The better conclusion is architectural. Where the tripod stands — regularity, exposure, honest feedback — intuition deserves not just tolerance but deference: making the surgeon 'show her working' in mid-operation is how committees kill patients. Where the tripod is missing, the task is not to exhort experts to introspect harder — introspection is precisely the instrument that cannot detect this fault — but to redesign their worlds: structure the interview, score the forecast, force the prediction into writing before the outcome arrives. The question 'should we trust intuition?' is, in the end, badly posed. It invites us to audit a feeling, when what can actually be audited is an environment. Ask instead where a judge's certainty was manufactured, and under what quality-control, and the mystery resolves into something almost administrative — which is, perhaps, why we resist resolving it. We would rather our oracles kept their smoke.",
